text:
does christmas bring you 'joy or pain'?
we are inbuilt to think christmas is a happy time, a time to share, a time to give, a time to be with loved ones, to remember loved ones, to eat more, drink more, have more....but what about those around you who don't enjoy this season. 
are you aware of that person at work who is not looking forward to christmas, or the friend who has no-one but is happy to be on their own this christmas, or the family around the corner who have nothing. maybe they could benefit from you, maybe they could enjoy a bit of company, maybe they could receive a nice donation of food.

maybe you are suffering at this time of year and don't know where to turn and are scared to reach out. don't be. there is support everywhere at this time of year, for us all. there is someone somewhere willing to support you, and if you are in doubt, how about calling the samaritans 116 123. 
today i am went to piaroos wish, helping the homeless in reading to support those in need at this time of year. it is colder, darker and harder. can you imagine if you had nothing?

when was the last time you stopped and spoke to someone on the streets or someone vulnerable around you? take a minute if you can and try it. you will be amazed at how important those few minutes could be to someone else. i love giving my time to others, and i thank those who have given their time to me. 
as i head into my festive season with my loved ones, i thank you all for supporting me this year in all of my activities. it has been an amazing year in so many ways, and i have learnt so much. but most of all i have learnt the value of giving back, in a much stronger way then i have ever done before. i have learnt the importance of my community and the strength everyone brings to my life, www.emmajanetaylor.life

text:
#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear it‚Äôs a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they don‚Äôt own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. ‚Äúthere is no greater threat to women than men? we‚Äôre the number one threat!‚Äù said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking ‚Äúlook at all that she can do for herself‚Äù. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult

for the woman who has experienced sexual trauma, you are not alone and there is hope for healing. maybe it's time to take the next step in your journey to heal. join us for the next seven week journey to heal women's group taking place at port city community church starting tuesday, january 15th from 6:30-8:30pm. groups are available at both the wilmington and leland campuses. registration is free, but required. learn more about jth groups and register for either location at www.journeytohealministries.org/programs/groups. text:
üå∏ so here i am gonna address the most prevalent problem in pakistan - child abuse. child abuse is a very sensitive issue that needs to be discussed so that people are aware about it. 
when we hear the term ‚Äúchild abuse" the only thing that comes to our mind is sexual harassment. but the most engrossing fact is that its not just sexual harassment.

child abuse can take any form : 
1) physical abuse (physical abuse is any forceful activity that can harm a child physically .its¬† when somebody purposely hurts a child like; beating, strangling) 
2) sexual abuse (sexual abuse is when an adult makes sexual contact with a child)
3) emotional abuse (when a child does not get the love and affection they deserve from¬† their parents/friends/classmates etc.)
4) neglect (when a child lacks things they need in order to grow like: shelter, education ,safety, etc.) following are the things we should consider doing:
1) it doesn't matter when child abuse has occured. your child needs counselling and care after such an incident.
2) make them emotionally strong.
3) you should be supportive and open to your child so they can share anything with you.
4) build a friendly relationship with them so they don't hesitate or feel ashamed sharing awkward situations they face. 
5) educate them on sexual harrasment. and teach them how to recognize the early signs and wrong touches.
6) keep a check on your child's activites.
7) don't trust any stranger with your child.
8) make them understand that its not their fault so that they never feel guilty about it.
9) dont let them feel lonely and listen to them carefully.
10) be a positive role model for your child. 
i hope you guys benefit from this message. share it with others aswell to spread awareness ‚ù§ . . . . . . .

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company ‚Äúweaponised‚Äù the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users‚Äô preferences for particular brands on social media platforms ‚Äì facebook, in particular ‚Äì were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign‚Äôs lesser reported ‚Äúweapons of mass destruction‚Äù. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone‚Äôs personality. a user‚Äôs predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call ‚Äúpopulist political signalling‚Äù. cambridge analytica, which was¬†shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump‚Äôs former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 ‚Äì including cultural preferences such as fashion and music ‚Äì to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
@lindsayjdraper don‚Äôt you wanna meet me at the gym?
.
by yourself or with a buddy, this one is a great workout! if your gym doesn‚Äôt have some of these things look around and see what they do have. you can always swap out exercises. üòâ we do the push ups and pull ups every week so we can master them and then switch out our circuits.
.
60 minutes-ish total body burner!
.
warm up: 10-15 minutes on a treadmill or stair master. get that ‚ô•Ô∏è rate going so you‚Äôre ready to work!
.
1Ô∏è‚É£: 3 sets of push ups alternated with 3 sets of assisted pull-ups. set weight appropriately. *
.
2Ô∏è‚É£: 3 sets of push ups (yes, more push-ups) alternated with 3 sets of lat pull down.
.
3Ô∏è‚É£: circuit training!! i love this part of the workout. we each pick three exercise that sound fun to us that day and set our timer for 1:00 minute of work and 15 second of rest to rotate to the next exercise. repeat 2x through. todays circuit:
.
- battle ropes
- weighted squats with a ball (ouch, quads!)
- weighted bulgarian split lunge, one keg the first time through and then swap the second time through - tricep extensions with the cable
- tire flip
- burpees with a bicep curl and shoulder press
.
get out there and give this one a try! then post it in your stories and tag me in it.
.
*if you‚Äôve never used this machine before it works differently than most machines. the goal here is to use less and less weight each time instead of more and more. if you chose 80lbs as your weight that means the machine is taking 80lbs off of your body weight. so 80 lbs less you‚Äôre pulling up. each time you head to the gym see if you can lower the number by just a few until you‚Äôre pulling up all your body weight!

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

trigger warning: mention of rape ‚ö†Ô∏è what was their fault? several people have been a victim of rape in this country, so many flowers were plucked before they could bloom, pure and innocent souls scarred for ever, their dreams and livelihood stolen from them, and pain and suffering is what was left.

rape does not just harm one physically but it is a mental trauma for the entire life. the survivors are scarred forever and get major mental health issues, like depression, insomnia, self neglecting, and so many more. it could also make one person suicidal and they could attempt to harm themselves.

what further deteriorates the situation is the lack of acceptance by the society for the victim. the survivor is blamed for the rape rather than the rapist, the clothes being too revealing is made a reason for blaming the victim. they are not accepted in this society and being a target of someone else's inhumanity results in their lives being destroyed whereas the rapist lives freely.

it's time for us to change. it's time for us to speak. it's time for us to fight for our rights. you are not responsible for it, someone else is, and they will bear the circumstances for doing such a thing, not you, because rape is wrong and its time to speak to stop the wrong. we can't let inhumane people ruin our lives, we can't let society blame the victim for being raped, and we will stand against the rape culture that exists in our society. it is time and you know it. -by sfm

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
everybody goes through ups and downs in their lives. they manifest what they believe and they believe what they‚Äôre taught. i obviously am very analytic and detail-oriented while also very, very emotional and empathetic.
i wasn‚Äôt deprived, malnourished, locked in my room and ignored. i had what i needed growing up and am grateful. but i looked so far into everything because i didn‚Äôt understand. i was/am obsessed with why people did/do such bad things, how people can be so selfish, why others are unable to empathize with the ones they ‚Äúlove‚Äù, and why it‚Äôs so hard to listen to someone with your full attention.
i experienced quite a bit of traumatic experiences in a short time, and wasn‚Äôt able to come to terms with it (and become who i am today) until years later. what i want to do is create a blog. i want to share my run-on thoughts, my doodles, my story, my favorite quotes, my interpretations of things. i want to help others, even if it‚Äôs just by assisting them in finding a new way to look at things. i want to show people that i may not have been in the exact same situations but i‚Äôm willing to mentally put myself there or look back on a situation i have been in to relate and offer the advice and affirmations i wish i‚Äôd had.
who would follow me once i create a website and all that? or who would help me make one? if i have the opportunity to help somebody feel valued, appreciated, understood and loved by getting personal and being transparent and vulnerable, i‚Äôll do it.
i feel that i can inspire others to love themselves regardless of where they fall in today‚Äôs standards and expectations.
@selflovewithsam gets credit for this quote on her story highlights! super touched and inspired by her which is why i was compelled to share today.‚ù§Ô∏è
contact me whenever, however. i‚Äôm open to any advice or support, per usual!

text:
posted on¬†december 11, 2018 3:20pm

a stay-at-home mom of three is firing back after a judge allegedly ‚Äúverbally assaulted‚Äù her ‚Äúfor mothering [her] children.‚Äù in¬†a facebook post¬†shared on nov. 21 that has since gone viral, fresno, california-based christa pehl evans recalled an incident the previous day that took place at the fresno superior courthouse, when judge james petrucelli would not allow her to be exempt from jury duty to take care of her kids. ‚Äúwhen i asked to be excused because i need to care for my children, these are things judge james petrucelli (dept. 61, fresno superior courthouse) said to me,‚Äù wrote pehl evans,¬†who is mom to son harvey, 5, plus daughters sylvia, 16 months, and violet, 7.

she went on to allege that she had been on the receiving end of comments from petrucelli such as, ‚Äúi don‚Äôt care about your children‚Äù and ‚Äúwho is going to take care of your children when you get hit by a mack truck?‚Äù pehl evans continued, ‚Äù ‚Äòwhat do you do when you are sick?‚Äô i replied, ‚Äòi take care of my kids,‚Äô and he shook his head at me with a disgusted expression on his face.‚Äù ‚Äù ‚Äòwhat do you do when you have to do something?‚Äô ‚Äù she claimed of another line of questioning. ‚Äúi replied, ‚Äòi take my baby.‚Äô ‚Äù

text_retweet:
kindly let me know when my story get posted.
this story is not really about me but about my parents. i think my mom and dad would have done their self a whole lot of good if they had never gotten married in the first place, from what we heard while growing up, both of them were match made by their parents hence that might be the reason they never loved each other. it's always from one fight to the other, the violence in our house is just too much, most times my dad is at fault but mom also does not know when to keep quiet, i hear the noise from my mom, the beatings, the hitting.... it's always one bruise or the other for my mom and i see it all despite the tons of makeup that covers it up, i'm 17 right now and i've seen it all and i can honestly say it's better having two happy separated parents than two miserable individuals that has refused to do themselves and the society a ton of good  by going on their separate ways all for the sake of flimsy excuses. i've advised my mom several times to go for divorce but guess she says? there has never been an history of divorce in her family so it can't start with her, also stones she says it's all because of us(her children) but i would feel a lot better if they're separated cause i'm scared that one day they would have a fight and she won't come out alive.  thanks for creating this platform @shareurxprience cause i've been looking for an avenue to let it all out for a while. 
#metoo
#myexperience
#notodomesticviolence
#notosexualharassment
#whyinevertalked
#sexualharassment
#mysilenceisnotmyconsent
#respectwomen
#storyofmylife
#mybodymydecision

text:
‚Äúthere is only one way to avoid criticism. do nothing, say nothing and be nothing‚Äù‚Äî aristotle. .
. the fact that you push forward when things try to hold you back is rewarding. it shows character. you are stronger than you know and once you look back and see what you have been through... you will see just how much you can handle. but don‚Äôt let that continue. you may have tolerated enough... now it‚Äôs time to step forward. make a stand and keep pressing forward. just because you fought through the pain does not mean you have to continue to live in it. walk through fire... but keep walking with the flames that carry your soul in strength and wisdom. .

personal updateüíû
the big moments in your life are made up by the little decisions you make.

i personally didn't make a big decision to get into an abusive relationship. i made a little decision to lower my integrity bar. i made another little decision to stay, when i saw the first signs that he didn't honor me the way i deserve to be honored. losing yourself over a someone who is lost is one of the worst things you could do to yourself.

it was my job to fall madly in love with myself first so i could set the example for others how to love me. 
you are the first example what loving you looks like and the way you love you is the way the world is going to love you. 
i'm here to incurage those who battle with whatever it is you're battling with to come forward and seek the help you need to feel betterüçÄ 
there's no reason for use to keep suffering in silence because the world is not ready for some real talk. 
so here's your friendly reminder to press reset today. it's never to late to fall madly in love with yourself firstüíï

no more shame!!!! xoxo #keep_it_happyhealth

100% yes!
.
while we need people who can come forward and share their trauma stories for a host of reasons, we also must make sure there is plenty of space for the countless folks who can't. that is the beauty in #metoo in its original creation. it was a safe way to find reciprocity. .
in order to find healing in sharing you need many conditions to be met and many people don't have those resources in place. one thing i love about my work is that it does not need narrative. .

text:
read what raquel has to say about what is actually taking place in an ista training. she took part in the level 1 training both as a participant and an assistant.

what is ista level 1? for outsiders

disclaimer - this is based on my experience, and everyone's experience is unique, because it's a deep process!

i first came across ista totally by chance; i was travelling with my beloved in guatemala and a poster caught my attention. probably because it had the word sex in it, and because it looked attractive and exotic. david and i signed up as a present to our love, not knowing what the week would be about. we are both grateful we took the plunge, as ista l1 is a well-oiled machine!

so why are people so mysterious about ista level 1? why can't they just give me the curriculum so i can decide if it's for me? the answer is simple; a lot of the transformational work that is done during that week needs to be in context. out of context it sounds nuts. i have done 2 level 1, once as a participant, and another time as an assistant, and i can guarantee that my learning and journey was unique each time. however, i understand that your mind wants something more palpable, so here goes.
in one sentence - ista level 1 is the education every human being should get when growing up.

boundaries - do you ever feel like you should have said no, but ended up saying yes? this relates to #metoo, but it also relates to those times when you accept too much responsibility at work, when you give a friend a shoulder although you really don't have the emotional strength at that moment, and other situations in which you are not clear about your boundaries and end up feeling depleted. ista level 1 explores this expertly from different angles, so even if you think you are brilliant with your boundaries (and the boundaries of others), you'll become better.

tools - even if you are content and emotionally switched on, there is space to become happier, more connected to your feelings, desires, fears, dreams‚Ä¶

read the full article on our facebook page facebook.com/awakemeditation/

or follow the link in our bio for more info on ista in portugal 
#tantra #istatribe #transformational #retreat

text:
another story of a young woman's experience with sexual assault.  this teen boy felt entitled to her body, which is why rape and rape culture continues....
"it was summer between ninth and tenth grade. my friends and i went to this boy's house. they had known him since grade school, but i had only met him that year. it was the middle of the day so his parents were at work. there were a bunch of us drinking and horsing around. some of my friends started to disappear into other rooms with their boyfriends or boys they liked. i remained in the den with the guy whose house it was. he eventually tried to kiss me and before i knew it, his hands were all over me. i was trying to push him off and he got even more determined. he got angry and began to fuss about how i liked other boys and how he was just as good as them. i was drunk and scared. the others heard the scuffle and came in and pulled him off of me. my friends and i left and from that day on i never saw him the same. i knew he was dangerous and i knew exactly what he was capable of." #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
outside the matrix 101: the weaponization of music

if you want to find the secrets of the universe, think in terms of energy, frequency and vibration.

god created the universe using sound, yah spoke and it was.

what i find amazing is how i am drawn to songs in 432 and how those songs give you chills or brings you to tears. when you listen to old vinyls you can feel the music in your soul. on a cd or mp3 you can only hear the music. many of bob marley's classics were made in 432hz, they have switched all modern songs to 440hz and worse.

i listened to the carpenters album in both frequencies. when i listened to the 440 hz, it felt like i was on edge or edgy and slightly off-centered in some way. then when i listened to the 432, it felt like sitting in a chair that was totally conformed to my body and felt centered, relaxed and peaceful.

the reason the wrong frequency is so dangerous to us is because we are mostly composed of water. look at the effects on water and understand that your body is made up of 60% water. music can change the frequency in your body. it changes the mood and energy instantly.

every sound in nature travels by wavelength. that wavelength is determined by frequency and amplitude. frequency is the actual pitch you hear. so, 440 or 432 refers to the frequency of the sound wave of the actual pitches that would be played in a scale. just like you can have a scale that starts on "c" or "c#" or "d" or any note you choose, modes start on whatever note you choose and then the pattern of half steps and whole steps between the pitches are what make a mode what it is.

432 is a vibration humans vibrate at peacefully. tesla's theory frequency vibration resonance. nothing happens ever without these three things happening. simple terms frequency= electricity, vibrations=vibrations, resonance =heat. we live in electric universe.

440 became the standard in the 1940's, after the information was discovered by the nazis and then spread globally after the war. the nazis scientist were imported into the west.

it's amazing how they have weaponized every single thing that reaches us through our senses.

text:
the plea deal of former baylor frat president jacob anderson on 4 charges of sexual assault is like a punch in the stomach to me as a survivor.
.
earlier this week, before this news broke, i told my counselor - "one of the hardest things for me is people who aren't outraged when someone is sexually assaulted."
.
for a perpetrator to sexually assault someone they have to dehumanize the victim to a certain extent. i believe the same is true when rulings such as this are issued. something else is put above the survivor, above this horrendous crime, above protecting future potential victims of this perpetrator.
.
on september 26, i was driving in my car when i heard the news of bill cosby's sentencing, and i cried. i cried because i know how hard to is for a survivor to come forward. i know how hard it is to get the police to charge your offender. i cried because not all cases that go to court result in a conviction. it was not just a victory for andrea constad, but also for every other survivor of bill cosby's crimes, and for every other #metoo survivor in the world. although 3 to 10 years doesn't even begin to match the punishment deserved, i cried tears of gratitude because that day one survivor had some amount of justice.
.
what happened to you is evil. nothing and no one's opinion lesson the truth of that. if you decide to report, and no charges are made - if it does go to court but there isn't a conviction - if there is a conviction, but the sentencing is like a slap in the face . . . none of that changes the truth that what happened to you is an atrocity.
.
what happened to you is horrendous. what happened to you is not your fault. surround yourself with people who do believe you. your story matters. you matter. keep fighting for yourself every day, you are worth more than you realize.
.
#believesurvivors #nomore #ibelieveyou #yourstorymatters #youmatter #timesup #keepfighting #andreaconstand #billcosby #jacobanderson #jacobwalteranderson #sexualassault #survivors #icwlh

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company ‚Äúweaponised‚Äù the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users‚Äô preferences for particular brands on social media platforms ‚Äì facebook, in particular ‚Äì were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign‚Äôs lesser reported ‚Äúweapons of mass destruction‚Äù. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone‚Äôs personality. a user‚Äôs predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call ‚Äúpopulist political signalling‚Äù. cambridge analytica, which was¬†shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump‚Äôs former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 ‚Äì including cultural preferences such as fashion and music ‚Äì to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users‚Äô preferences for particular brands on social media platforms ‚Äì facebook, in particular ‚Äì were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign‚Äôs lesser reported ‚Äúweapons of mass destruction‚Äù. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone‚Äôs personality. a user‚Äôs predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call ‚Äúpopulist political signalling‚Äù. cambridge analytica, which was¬†shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump‚Äôs former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 ‚Äì including cultural preferences such as fashion and music ‚Äì to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

let's talk, research and find a way to deal with domestic violence in a just manner that has true accountability.

text:
(reuters) - attorneys for bill cosby outlined their grounds on tuesday for appealing his sexual assault conviction, citing what they called errors in legal procedure that may have biased the jury and warrant a new trial for the once-beloved comedian. the 81-year-old performer, best known for his role as the lovable family man and physician on the hit television sitcom ‚Äúthe cosby show,‚Äù was found guilty by a pennsylvania jury in april of drugging and sexually assaulting a onetime friend in 2004.

it marked the first such criminal conviction of a celebrity accused of sexual misconduct since the #metoo movement that has brought down dozens of powerful, privileged men in american media, politics and business since the autumn of 2017.

in september, the trial judge, steven o‚Äôneill, designated cosby a ‚Äúsexually violent predator‚Äù under pennsylvania law, requiring the entertainer to register as a sex offender for life, and sentenced him to a term of three to 10 years in prison.

cosby, who is married, has insisted all along that any sexual encounters he had were consensual. he was found guilty on three counts of aggravated indecent assault.

in an eight-page filing laying out the basis of their appeal, cosby‚Äôs lawyers focused on several instances they said introduced bias into the trial, including the judge‚Äôs refusal to excuse a juror that the defense argued was unable to be fair and impartial. #freebillcosby #farfromfinished #justice #corruption #thecosbyshow #blackexcellence #wronglyconvicted #billcosby

text:
matt lauer accused of sexual harassment by multiple women: as the co-host of nbc‚Äôs ‚Äútoday,‚Äù matt lauer once gave a colleague a sex toy as a present. it included an explicit note about how he wanted to use it on her, which left her mortified. he would sometimes quiz female producers about who they‚Äôd slept with, offering to trade names. and he loved to play a crass game with men and women in the office: ‚Äúf‚Äî, marry, or kill,‚Äù in which he would identify the female co-hosts that he‚Äôd most like to sleep with.

these accounts of lauer‚Äôs behavior at nbc are the result of a two-month investigation by variety, with dozens of interviews with current and former staffers. variety has talked to three women who identified themselves as victims of sexual harassment by lauer, and their stories have been corroborated by friends or colleagues that they told at the time. they have asked for now to remain unnamed, fearing professional repercussions. #metoo

text:
looking out on a grey sky ready to attend a meeting to decide my future... feeling so anxious, out of control & completely emotional.. üòêüôÑüò• am i technically 'incapable' of performing my duties as a teacher for the foreseeable future???? üòëüò∂üôÑ that seems to have already been decided... but what to do with me now???ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è i have fought so hard to get where i am...something that i have always been ridiculed for by my family..."your such a disaster, why do you make everything so difficult, you'll never manage that!"‚ò¢ ü§îüò∂üôÑüò•üò™üòüüò≠üö´üë®‚Äçüë©‚Äçüëß‚Äçüë¶ yes, it took me about 7 years to complete my first masters degree (after i escaped from unbearable hell at home age 16) i worked 3 jobs, suffered great personal loss, including bereavement, domestic violence, rape, narcisstic & emotional abuse. i sacrificed my needs for family & friends & i did it with adhd, crippling anxiety, agoraphobia, depression, bpd & other mental health problems & crap i hid from the world (& myself)üò∂üôÑü§® but...i got through it...maybe just, but... i survived...üí™ü§ûüëä i also managed to travel the world, fit in marriage, buy a house then complete another degree for a full career change before i was 30! but its only today that i can actually admit these things happened to me! good & bad! i can feel the pain & deal with it... but i am also learning i can be proud of my achievements & actually they mean more after accepting what i have had to overcome üòä

it's only now... when i'm faced with everything being taken away from me, that i can see...im not 'bad' or 'hard work'... i am humanüòê i am flawed, beaten but not brokenüòÄüòâ‚ò∫üí™ i am determined...i will not let anyone else control the outcome of my life with doubts, lies or painüíîü§û‚ù§ *so scared to post this!! hate being so vulnerable & honest but without this we cant make change!

text:
it was alone in my bed that i first knew. my mind looped over and over what he did. in the quiet darkness with no escape and no distractions i finally listened.
my stomach felt sick as my mind replayed each time he raped me. it‚Äôs three years later an instead of sleeping my brain still tells me the same nightmare.
i can say i‚Äôm fine.
i can breathe and take my meds.
i can journal and exercise and tell myself the truth.
but at night it all comes back.
too tired to reason with myself, i experience it all again, and again, and again.
i just want to sleep.
but i cannot.
i cannot forget the way his voice sounds.
i cannot forget the way he slept beside me.
i cannot forget the way his body felt against mine.
i cannot unlove him, and it‚Äôs killing me.

as part of our migration month, we‚Äôre exploring the specific ways in which women are uniquely affected by the crossing of borders. such crossings are often violent, exploitative and coercive. according to the united nations, women account for 71 percent of trafficking victims, with sexual exploitation being the most common type.

.

"the takeaway of harvey weinstein‚Äôs recent i‚Äôve-had-one-hell-of-year e-mail could easily apply to the fashion industry, too."
*
"while the year started with media reports of bombshell allegations of sexual misconduct and abuse against major league photographers, plenty of other firestorms erupted in the months that followed. reports of overly handsy executives, a dearth of non-slender models on the runway, victoria secret‚Äôs alarmingly non-#metoo-fashion show and¬†dolce & gabbana‚Äôs public apology for offensive instagram posts against the chinese were just some of the fiery issues that seared the fashion crowd throughout 2018."
*
"the need for greater diversity permeated on many levels ‚Äî runway shows, advertising shoots, c-suites, women‚Äôs empowerment and in editorial. from start to finish, there were calls for more diversity, inclusivity and respect. building from the momentum first sparked by last year‚Äôs women‚Äôs march and the groundswell of support for the #metoo and time‚Äôs up movements, women and people of all persuasions increasingly voiced their opinion."
*
"after published reports of alleged sexual abuse, kering and lvmh mo√´t hennessy louis vuitton issued a charter for models in the fall of 2017, and then cond√© nast and tapestry inc. ‚Äî parent of coach and kate spade ‚Äî released ones of their own for photo/video shoots and fashion shows and presentations with the intention of safeguarding those who work with the companies. the cfda emphasized the importance of creating a safe environment, asking designers, show producers and photographers to consider using venues for shoots and runway shows that have areas where models can change in privacy."
*
"in may, 100 models banded together to create a program to try to end sexual harassment in the fashion industry. led by the model alliance‚Äôs founder sara ziff, the new ‚Äúrespect‚Äù program asks brands, modeling agencies and media outlets to sign a legally binding agreement to protect models."

text: ternion: 16 x 16 in, acrylic on canvas. ternion is a grouping of three. i‚Äôve been thinking a lot about relationships lately. with so many changes happening in so many lives, politics encroaching every aspect of our conversations and the seasonal stress of the holidays, our collective souls have lost a bit of empathy with strangers... and friends. as much as we are different, we are all the same. the trinity here is: you, me and the space we share. i could speak of family, shed some light on the elephant in the room for those that think they know my situation. i could write about my post the other day remembering a shot of tequila with a politician that‚Äôs got his eye on the presidential election of 2020 and the vitriol that erupted for no reason. i could talk about the weekend of festiveness shared with my grandmother and a friend, which would‚Äôve been fun to share with others as well. but, instead, i‚Äôll talk about you and me and the circle we share. it isn‚Äôt the space between that drives us apart; it‚Äôs the space together that‚Äôs shared without respect that hurts us all. i‚Äôve always loved circles, the symbology of an everlasting embrace. by posting my paintings and writing a bit about them, i‚Äôm inviting you into my space. by looking at this, you are entering my circle to create another. it‚Äôs a simply understood allegory. but, also, we do this everyday from buying a cold drink at 7-11 and the exchange with the cashier, holding the door at the mall to help someone with their hands full to tapping a heart on instagram or commenting on a fb post. in this crazy world with so many layers of color and chaos, it‚Äôs easy to forget every interaction we have with another is over lapping our circle, creating new ones which effect people‚Äôs lives in big and small ways. this is that reflection. #livingwithart #jennifire #circleoflife #attitudeofgratitude #happinessishere #wednesdaywisdom #seasonsgreetings #mindfulness #acrylicpainting #embrace #metoo #spraydaily #simplelife  #womenartists #dallasart #glasslife #weareone #respectyourself #oprahsbookclub #respectlife #strongertogether #artlove  #womenwriters #meditation #plur #plurlife #blessup #soulshine #lovequotes #lifelesson

text: l'attrice argentina thelma fardin (giusy nella serie), conosciuta per aver preso parte alla serie tv "il mondo di patty", ha denunciato un collega attore, juan darth√©s (leandro padre di patty nella serie), accusandolo di averla violentata in nicaragua nel 2009, quando lei aveva 16 anni e lui 45. darthes era il promotore della serie, interpretata da giovani aspiranti attrici minorenni. le parole di fardin hanno suscitato immediatamente la solidariet√† dell'associazione attrici argentine e oltre 100 donne che ne fanno parte si sono fatte fotografare con lei, in un gesto che oggi √® sulle prime pagine di molti giornali a buenos aires. darthes ha negato i fatti, scrivendo su twitter: "√® pazzesco, non √® mai successo nulla". fardin ha spiegato di essersi convinta a parlare grazie al movimento niunamenos, versione argentina del #metoo di hollywood: ha trovato il coraggio di denunciare durante una conferenza stampa in un teatro della capitale argentina, mostrando un video molto forte, in cui tra le lacrime racconta i dettagli del presunto stupro, poi condiviso anche su instagram.

text:
how do we improve the workplace for disabled employees?
mencap‚Äôs #hereiam campaign identifies ‚Äúthere are 1.4 million people in the uk with a learning disability‚Äù, yet ‚Äújust 6% of people with a learning disability known to social services are in paid employment‚Äù.
we need to ensure our workplaces offer a supportive and inclusive environment for disabled employees.
employers have a duty to make reasonable adjustments to ensure disabled employee can carry out their role ‚Äì particularly if the current place, practice or procedure of an organisation unfairly disadvantages an employee with a disability. it is important to note here that employers who do not adhere to their duty to provide reasonable adjustments risk discriminating against disabled employees.
reasonable adjustments may include allocated parking spaces closer to the office building, a desk with adjustable height, allowing for regular breaks, offering flexible working or providing an employee with a mentor.
so how do we ensure we provide this supportive environment where reasonable adjustments can be made? by opening up the conversation and asking disabled employees how they can be supported to help them fulfil their role ‚Äì asking, rather than assuming, or worse, box ticking!  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

text:
hey folks. the past week i‚Äôve been inpatient. instead of planning for finals last week i planned my death. it was such a weird place to be in my head. recent events triggered my ptsd and it spiraled out of control honestly. i stopped eating, thinking that my body was trying to kill me anyways, might as well help it along. i stopped drinking water and got awful headaches and cramps. one of my friends left my life(which i was okay with) but it didn‚Äôt help my already poor health. 
my heart would pound out of my chest from the time i woke up to the time i fell asleep. i wanted to do it without medicine, which was stupid because now that i‚Äôm medicated, my heart beats a lot closer to normal. my friends i thought would be better off without me actually care and i still get to take my finals, so my hard work won‚Äôt be for nothing like i thought. i was knocked down but i‚Äôm not out for the count yet. it feels all too personal, but i never want anyone to feel this way, to feel so alone and misunderstood. please reach out if you feel like suicide is your only option. i love you, please stay strong. 
#ptsd#womenempowerment#anxiety#depression#survivor#metoo#keepitreal#onedayatatime#mentalhealth#womenarestrong#littlefighter#bigdreamer

text:
where, after all, do universal human rights begin? in small places, close to home -- so close and so small that they cannot be seen on any maps of the world. [...] unless these rights have meaning there, they have little meaning anywhere. without concerted citizen action to uphold them close to home, we shall look in vain for progress in the larger world." -- eleanor roosevelt
teaching young girls their rights is the first step to preventing or reducing abuse, because when is aware she reports to the right  channel when she sees or experiences other wise, and in doing so we are reducing the cases of abuse and the number of broken adults due to abusive childhood in the society.

text:
the #metoo from argentina. 
under the hashtag #miracomonosponemos, more than 500 argentine actresses gave a press conference yesterday to support the rape complaint of actress thelma fardin against actor juan darth√©s when she was 16 y/o. yesterday,  9 years later, fardin spoke out so others can hear her too. #argentina has been at the forefront of latin america in some of the feminist claims. in this country was born, in 2015, the movement #niunamenos against #femicides that later was replicated in the rest of the continent. in 2017 they organized the first women's strike in the region and this year was marked by the collective struggle for the legalization of #abortion, which was finally stopped in the senate and authorized only in some cases. in south america, only uruguay allows women to freely decide on the interruption of their pregnancy. link in bio. #miracomonosponemos #thelmafardin #metoo #womensrights #genderviolence #actricesargentinas

text: this story is called: 1 train, 30 minutes and 2 men. today on my way to work i almost missed the train. luckily for me, the driver open again the door so i got in and even got enough time to hold the door for a 50+ year old man behind me. i sit down and 7 stops later a young guy gets on the train with a banana on one hand and a painting on the other. he suddenly asked me ‚Äòdo you want a banana?‚Äô i prepared myself to say no thank you and he added ‚Äòthe banana in my pants‚Äô. i told him not to do that shit ever again to any women and try to make him understand why what he said was disrespectful. he couldn‚Äôt care less - he said i clearly have gone through some shit and that‚Äôs why i didn‚Äôt appreciate his comment (aren‚Äôt we all women went through a kid of this stupid shit?!) - i thought to myself ok at least is daytime and if i need help i‚Äôm sure the old guy will help me. wrong! the train stopped at my station i got up - the old guy got up and gave me this note... i guess dave is also not a safe guy to go to! as a souvenir, i got a banana in my purse and a note from old creep dave in my fist. feel free to show dave some love: 6466707717. #metoo #showdavesomelove

text:
mercury re-enters sagittarius .
.

mercury is moving forwards, crossing back into the flashing lights of #sagittarius tonight, on december 12, where they began their retrograde journey on november 16. sagittarius is the sign of the guru, prophet, or priest; ruled by #jupiter, who wants to bring justice, but who‚Äôs mythology is a mixture of good and ill behavior. it is fitting then that as mercury worked their way out of #scorpio--jupiter in scorpio brought us the #metoo movement--towards sag, sexual abuse allegations emerged against a popular spiritual healer, john of god, in brazil. .
.

more and more people are seeking spiritual solutions to the big issues facing our world, but, inevitably, as we go deeper into this arena, and as spiritual practices expand, we encounter abuse of power. the curative powers of john of god are world renowned. how disillusioning then, that the individual could be harmful when the energy flowing through him was healing. it is hard to square this, but mercury in sagittarius will not look away. the winged messenger delivers the truth whether we want it, or are ready for it, or not. this dispersing fire energy will be with us for the remainder of the year, causing our minds to dash and dart this way and that. it‚Äôs not the most serene feeling. mercury in sag likes to get up on a high horse, but they are also seeking the small, tangible solution to the larger spiritual problem. .
.

what can each of us do today to #believewomen and support survivors? one tangible step is to call to tennessee governor bill haslam urging him to grant clemency to #cyntoiabrown a survivor of sex trafficking who was sentenced to 51 years for murdering her abuser. we can contrast her case with brock turner‚Äôs lenient sentence of 6 months for rape to understand the unjust consequences of racial and gender bias in the legal system. .
.

mercury is moving into a conjunction with jupiter that will perfect on the #wintersolistice. as we move towards the longest night, may each of us be small beacons lighting the way for each other as we travel the path towards death and rebirth. 
#astrology #queerastrology #freecyntoia #endrape

text:
new class to zenon: fundamental improvisation/contact improvisation taught by taja will. for our winter/spring session, sundays 2-3:30pm!
@tajawillxo 
photo: nanne sorvold
.

this class will focus on the intersections of structured improvisation, somatic modalities and contact improvisation skills. structured improvisation will serve to inform our body's connections to elements such as space, time, geometry and range. somatic modalities serve to inform our embodied relationship to ourselves, anatomical intelligence, our choices and how they echo within a space. contact improvisation will be the vehicle for movement that seeks relationship, textures of touch and our consent to be in dialogue with a partner or ensemble.
.

as a fundamental part of my pedagogy i employ a restorative justice lens to these ways of moving. i am interested in using language that acknowledges systems of power, privilege and the historical marginalization of individuals who are bipoc, queer, non-binary, trans, and artists with disabilities. 
in the era of #metoo i am committed to boldly transparent consent in touch based dance forms. 
it is my intention to develop this awareness in every class for bolder, safer spaces of inclusion. - taja will diversity & inclusion consultant & facilitator
.

taja will is a queer, chilean adoptee, performer, choreographer, therapist and restorative justice facilitator. her approach integrates improvisation, somatic modalities, text and vocals in contemporary  performance. will‚Äôs aesthetic is one of spontaneity, bold choice making, sonic and kinetic partnership and the ability to move in relationship to risk and intimacy.  she explores visceral connections to current socio-cultural realities through archetypes and everyday magic.
.
.
.
.

#fundamentalimprovisation #fundamentalcontactimprovisation #improvisation #contactimprovisation #learnimprovisation #learncontactimprovisation #improv #newclass #tajawill #dance #zenondance #wewillmoveyou

text:
tools for releasing üôèüèº‚ú®
.
if you read my last post you‚Äôll know a little bit about what helped me release negative energy after my sexual assault. (if you haven‚Äôt read the last post - giirrlll, go read that first!) üíÅüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
the thing about trauma or any kind of negative experience is that it isn‚Äôt just surface level.
.
negative energy, trauma, and deep physical or emotional pain all go deep into our soul and into the core of our being!
.
think about it like this: imagine you just spilled red wine on your shirt. in order to make sure it doesn‚Äôt stain you need to clean it asap.
.
but what if you don‚Äôt clean it immediately... or what if you clean it a bit but miss a spot?!
.
the wine will sink into the microfibres of the shirt. it seeps in and has time to soak up there... becoming way more nestled and habituated!
.
there is still a chance you can get the stain out, but now it‚Äôs going to take more time, energy, and effort because it started to become part of the fibre. it‚Äôs no longer separate... it‚Äôs like it‚Äôs become a natural part of the clothing!
.
this is exactly the same thing when it comes to deep pain. most of us release a little bit and then bottle it up. we hide it from others and try to forget about it, hoping it will just disappear with time! but the longer we hold onto it the deeper rooted it becomes, and the more engrained and permanent it seems.
.
i truly believe in a holistic and well-rounded approach to release these things. i don‚Äôt think there is a one-size-fits-all model, because we are unique and everyone has different experiences and beliefs that need to be accounted for.
.
but here are some examples of different methods i‚Äôve used on myself or with my clients:
-meditation
-energy healing (like reiki)
-inner child and shadow work
-clearing subconscious patterning
-mindset shifts
-neurolinguistic programming
-chakra balancing
-tibetan heart yoga
... among others!
.
but aside from those, what is most important is creating a safe space to dive headfirst into these issues. we cannot continue to push them aside if we want to truly heal and release the negative energy or limiting patterns that surround them! üíï

text:
i want you to repeat after me and i'll be repeating this to myself as well: "taking care of myself doesn't mean 'me first,' it means 'me too!"' we take care of others, especially the ones we love, and that's a wonderful quality and a kind way to be, yet we need to remember to include ourselves in that "taking care of" process.

taking care of yourself isn't selfish or putting yourself first, although there are times you need to put yourself first, especially when you're feeling drained, tired or exhausted. you're of no use to anyone unless you're well rested, healthy and balanced. and you know that.

so, today i want you to remind yourself that you're not saying "me first" by taking care of yourself, you're simply including yourself in taking care of others by saying "me too." and that is a good thing! <3

wishing you love and light, ~anne dennish~

#metoo #takingcareofyourself #takingcareofothers #balance #loveyourself #anne_dennish #wakingup #quotes

.
.
‚Äúsince we‚Äôre here talking about education, i wanted to ask a question about one of your tennessee students and a graduate of #lipscombuniversity, cyntoia brown,‚Äù laing said, to audience applause. "as a victim of sex trafficking and assault, this is an unjust sentence in the first place,‚Äù laing said. .
.
under tennessee law, all minors engaged in¬†#sexwork¬†are legally considered victims of sex trafficking. .

.

.

governor haslam reiterated that his office is talking to everyone involved in brown‚Äôs case, will have a decision on clemency before he leaves office in six weeks. .

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
for years i spoke pro bono, refusing to receive $$, because the simple thought of sharing my story and getting paid made me feel as though i was exploiting it. it took me a number of years and a handful of mentors to help me realize that my story has value and that to accept compensation gave me the rare opportunity (not right) to have a far greater reach. now, not only do i get paid to do work that i‚Äôm incredibly proud of, but i also have the ability to continually invest further in my speaking career.
‚Ä¢
speaking into people‚Äôs lives...it‚Äôs a privilege and not one i take lightly. unfortunately, the more i‚Äôve ventured into the world of professional speaking, the more i‚Äôve realized that there are countless speakers out there who are merely speaking to be heard & seen, rather than to see & hear. countless speakers who measure their worth by the # of gigs they get, the amount of followers (not relationships) they have, and the amount of $$ in their bank accounts.
‚Ä¢
it breaks my heart that audiences act surprised when i stay after events to offer love, support and guidance to anyone who needs it. surprised that instead of collecting my paycheck and darting for the door, i make it a priority to take the time to personally pour into them. and surprised that i provide my personal phone number at each event and offer calls to anyone who just needs a listening ear.
‚Ä¢
it breaks my heart. that as a society we‚Äôve gotten to a place where we prioritize our ‚Äúhustle‚Äù for
fame
exposure
&
‚Äúsuccess‚Äù
- o v e r -
empathy and connection.
‚Ä¢
as speakers, we‚Äôre supposed to be helping others to shine light in their darkness, not selfishly and greedily stealing the light for ourselves.
‚Ä¢
if you have a story to share with the world, one rooted in empathy that encourages and empowers others to find light, and you‚Äôre ready to invest in the value of your story, then send me a dm or comment below and i can help you take that step. as a speaking coach for the #micdropworkshop , i‚Äôm offering free coaching sessions (normal value of $250) for anyone who signs up for our upcoming course by this sunday. check the link in my bio for more info. can‚Äôt wait to walk this journey with you!

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
2018. a year that will go down in history as the year of women. the year feminism fought back. i have been so inspired this year by the stories of empowered women fighting back against injustices and making sure their stories are heard. the past few days i‚Äôve been keeping up with the jacob anderson case, and i believe it is time for me to share my story with the world.

i am a survivor of sexual assault and stalking from june. i learned the hard way that what we had wasn‚Äôt love like i though it was. it was lust under the guise of love. what angers me more than the mental and physical abuse i‚Äôve endured by men is the way my university handled it when i spoke out and reported. 
university case determinations are based on the preponderance of evidence standard, meaning charges occur when they believe the event more likely than not occurred (a 51% chance). my case was settled on september 26. i went into the office and sat down in front of a 45-page report with the words not responsible in all caps and bolded. i had evidence and witness statements of the stalking, but was told in an interview that they ‚Äúweren‚Äôt really as concerned with that as the assault.‚Äù therefore stalking wasn‚Äôt even listed under the charges, the one thing i had indisputable evidence for, but that wasn‚Äôt even what upset me the most.

in the beginning of the report they list staf 1.08 which contains the university‚Äôs definition of consent. 
consent is  defined as an uncoerced, enthusiastic ‚Äúyes.‚Äù in my investigator‚Äôs summary of notes from one of the meetings with my respondent (my attacker) he wrote, ‚Äúrespondent states there was not ‚Äúa verbal word ‚Äòyes,‚Äô but it was the same routine and she was engaged.‚Äù they acknowledge that consent was never asked for and that i never gave a verbal ‚Äúyes,‚Äù but because it was the same routine and i was silent/absent of resistance they considered it consent. this was a lot to deal with. to sit across from a man and essentially be told my story was invalid. i‚Äôm here to share my story to show everyone that you are not alone. your story is valid whether you report or not. your trauma is valid and is not to be compared to others‚Äô. you are valid.
#metoo #believesurvivors

text:
l'attrice argentina thelma fardin, conosciuta per aver preso parte alla serie tv "il mondo di patty", ha denunciato un collega attore, juan darth√©s, accusandolo di averla violentata in nicaragua nel 2009, quando lei aveva 16 anni e lui 45.¬†darthes era il promotore della serie, interpretata da giovani aspiranti attrici minorenni. le parole di fardin hanno suscitato immediatamente la solidariet√† dell'associazione attrici argentine e oltre 100 donne che ne fanno parte¬†si sono fatte fotografare con lei, in un gesto che oggi √® sulle prime pagine di molti giornali a buenos aires. darthes ha negato i fatti,¬†scrivendo su twitter: "√® pazzesco, non √® mai successo nulla". fardin ha spiegato di essersi convinta a parlare grazie al movimento niunamenos, versione argentina del¬†#metoo di hollywood: ha trovato il coraggio di denunciare durante una conferenza stampa in un teatro della capitale argentina, mostrando un video molto forte, in cui tra le lacrime racconta i dettagli del presunto stupro, poi¬†condiviso anche su instagram. "tornando dalla piscina mi sono accorta che mi si era smagnetizzata la scheda per aprire la porta dell'hotel", racconta thelma nel video. darth√©s le disse, afferma l'attrice, di andare in camera sua e chiedere per telefono che gliene fosse portata un'altra. "accettai", spiega thelma, "ma mentre ero al telefono ha cominciato a baciarmi sul collo e non si √® fermato pi√π". nel video fardin racconta tutti i particolari della violenza - portata a termine ma interrotta da qualcuno che buss√≤ alla porta, dice - e dedica le ultime sequenze ai volti delle attrici solidali che guardando fissa la telecamera sfidano il presunto stupratore. durante la conferenza stampa √® poi emerso che l'attore accusato del gesto avrebbe perfino partecipato alla realizzazione di uno spot del ministero dello sviluppo sociale contro la violenza di genere, che ora l'istituto nazionale delle donne avrebbe deciso di ritirare da tutti gli account dei suoi social network.

text:
‚Äòmy story is your story and your story is my story‚Äô
2018 has been one of the biggest and most transformational years for me and many of the women i know.

deep and profound changes are afoot both personally and collectively and i have had more enquires than ever before from women looking for a local circle where they can gather with other women and share what is going on for them in their world.

collectively, this year has also been a huge year for us to finally face and respond to the massive gaps in human equality relating to gender and race. it is no longer an option to sit silently by. we are being called (or called-out in some cases) to stand up, use our voices and take responsibility for our personal (and often unwitting) compliance. we are being called to support our sisters as they speak up and out against violence and abuse and oppression.

we are also being forced to take personal responsibility for the way we treat our planet and the different species we share it with, and to be more informed and activated about the current economic and politics state of the world. there is no doubt to anyone who is halfway awake that we are in a time of great change with an uncertain outcome.

that all being said, i also hold great hope that we are not too late to change the trajectory of these times. as i search my conscience for my own personal part to play, i keep coming back to the knowing that connection is key. connection to ourselves, connection to each other, connection to this beautiful planet and the other beings we share it with, and connection to spirit.

harambee in swahili, literally means ‚Äôpulling or working together' and i am seeing this everywhere. whether it is in women gathering in circles, young people mobilising over climate change and animal rights or women bravely standing up and saying #metoo.

as the sister circles continues to evolve, and more women meet in circle all around the world, we are gathering a great network of women who are taking responsibility for themselves and then turning around to assist our sisters.

for more... see the link in bio xxx

text:
our #womancrushwednesday goes out to a woman whom @oprah calls a mentor-the brilliant, brave and barrier-busting @drmayaangelou! she was born in the segregated south and challenged assumptions about what poor black girls could do. she had an incredibly productive writing career, with 30 books to her credit, but she‚Äôs probably best known for her six memoirs-the first was ‚Äúi know why the caged bird sings.‚Äù long before the #metoo movement, the book details her experience with sexual trauma-her mom‚Äôs boyfriend raped her when she was very young. he was tried and convicted but murdered before he could serve time. she didn‚Äôt speak for nearly five years, believing her voice killed him. she says only her love of literature brought back her voice. her first memoir became a best-seller, during a time when most publishers didn‚Äôt think black women‚Äôs lives were worthy of autobiography. she had several other jobs and broke many barriers - she was san francisco's first female african-american cable car conductor, at the age of 16. she was also one of the first african-american female members of the director's guild of america. her career in the arts wasn't limited to writing - maya angelou was also a singer, a calypso dancer and a broadway actress. she won three grammy awards for best spoken word albums, and she won a tony for her role in the 1972 play, look away. she also holds 50 honorary degrees.

in 1993, president-elect bill clinton invited her to read an original poem at his inauguration - only the second poet in american history to receive the honor. (know who the first poet was? and whose inauguration he read at? post your answer in the comments!) in 2011, former president barack obama awarded her the highest civilian honor -  the presidential medal of freedom. maya angelou was all about love and inclusivity: she believed we are more alike than unalike, regardless of our ethnic, religious and cultural differences. she died in 2014 at the age of 86. 
#wcw #womenempowerment #womeninspiringwomen #dogoodbegood @mistressmarquam @iammichaelfaith @m.k.ulta @annemarieluthro @evantia_maria @dirtgirl.bader.26

(know who the first poet was? and whose inauguration he read at? post your answer in the comments!) in 2011, former president barack obama awarded her the highest civilian honor -  the presidential medal of freedom. maya angelou was all about love and inclusivity: she believed we are more alike than unalike, regardless of our ethnic, religious and cultural differences. she died in 2014 at the age of 86.

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company‚Äôs problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you‚Äôre building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person‚Äôs psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the ‚Äútraining set‚Äù refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your ‚Äúfeature set‚Äù: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it‚Äôs facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data ‚Äì the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you‚Äôre trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text: @igrannapp from @nytimes: on a monday night in midtown #manhattan, a group of approximately 20 men were baring their #souls. ‚Äúi‚Äôm angry that my health is deteriorating. i‚Äôm not ready to be an old man,‚Äù said jeff nichols who‚Äôs 70. ranging in age from 30 to 70, the men were gathered as part of the @themankindproject (mkp), a 33-year-old nonprofit with 24 chapters in the u.s. and 11 regions abroad. it focuses on things like men‚Äôs emotional well-being, drawing on elements like carl jung‚Äôs theories of the psyche, nonviolent communication, breath work and native american customs. men, who are less likely than women to seek out individual therapy, are increasingly looking for outlets in this fraught cultural moment of political acrimony, widespread economic instability and major societal reckoning over their behavior. at mkp, membership is at an all-time high and enrollment is up 8% over the last year, said boysen hodgson, the director of marketing and communications. ‚Äúwith time‚Äôs up now and #metoo, many men know they have to be more accountable,‚Äù boysen said. ‚Äúa lot of them are saying, ‚Äòi don‚Äôt want that to be me. i don‚Äôt want that to be how #men are seen in the world.‚Äô‚Äù @caseykelbaugh took this photo during an mkp weekly meeting in manhattan. visit the link in our profile to read more.

text:
finally, witches, after notallmen arsery and aaaalll sundry shitfuckery, here‚Äôs #womanup. this is the first stage: we need you! it won‚Äôt work without every witch contributing, so #toyourbrooms. 
what‚Äôs it all about? well, it goes back to this post from october:
https://www.facebook.com/229308590735867/posts/742534912746563/

in response to that, which went fucking crazy, our founder wrote a piece on @womensagenda (google that plus jennie hill). so. this made us think. about how women routinely don‚Äôt report, and #metoo featured only those who could. about how women want desperately to talk, yet have been unable. about how those who do speak are punished, ridiculed, ostracised and disbelieved. about how perps therefore go free and this leads directly to more violence and women‚Äôs and children‚Äôs deaths. and about how this has to change. stat. we can‚Äôt affect change unless we see the fucking problem. 
here‚Äôs where you come in. post reports of sexual misconduct to us, as it‚Äôs the only foolproof way to speak anonymously. here‚Äôs how: - write about your experiences (one or more) of sexual harassment, sexual assault and/or rape. describe what happened and the aftermath: what happened next, were you believed, and how did your life change? - write 10 words minimum and 400 maximum, preferably hand-written (type only if you can‚Äôt hand-write);
- use one side only of one sheet of paper/card; - put your name and/or contact deets on the reverse (they‚Äôll remain anonymous but supply additional authenticity): if you can‚Äôt, participate but add an explanation of why you require absolute anonymity;
- don‚Äôt name perpetrators or clearly identify culpable situations/people; - post to p. o. box 451, daylesford, vic, 3460; and
-  like/comment/share this post to your networks. 
financial support is always optional, but there‚Äôs a heavy workload here, so consider including a small(ish) banknote with your letter, or contribute to patreon or paypal, or message for account deets (and for men not contributing, this plus sharing is your way to contribute): http://paypal.me/madwitches
https://www.patreon.com/madfuckingwitches

#womanup could be big. please get involved, we need you!
