text:
there is a stereotype that‚Äôs often attached to mental illness: those struggling are seen as dangerous, unpredictable, incompetent, and at fault for a disorder they have no control over. that‚Äôs why it was shocking when on june 5th,¬†kate spade was found dead¬†from a confirmed suicide in her park avenue home. then, three days later, reports broke that¬†anthony bourdain had taken his own life. from the outside looking in, neither spade, a legendary fashion designer and style icon, nor bourdain, a celebrated chef, author, television host, and noted #metoo ally, looked ‚Äúthe part.‚Äù they were both powerful, wealthy, successful, and beloved, with millions of adoring fans ‚Äî fans who had no idea they were suffering.

but the truth is, mental illness does not discriminate. one in five adults in the united states has a¬†mental health condition, and according to a report from the centers for disease control and prevention, the¬†nation‚Äôs suicide rate is on the rise. from 1999 to 2016, the number of americans who died by suicide increased by 28 percent.

in the wake of spade and bourdain‚Äôs tragic deaths, countless people have taken to social media to share empathetic messages of love and support for anyone struggling with¬†depression or suicidal thoughts, which is a hopeful reminder of how far the conversation around mental illness has come in the states.

but if #afriend has confided in you about their own severe depression or suicidal thoughts, it can be hard to¬†know how to help. that is why hellogiggles asked experts to share tips for navigating this difficult subject. while there is no one right answer when it comes to mental health, these small things can make a big difference in the lives of your loved ones. #feelingalone

text:
when i found out that emily giffen has released her ninth book, ‚Äúall we ever wanted,‚Äù i requested it at the library, got put on hold, and promptly forgot about it. last week i was pleasantly surprised learn that the book was available. around this time of the year the mood for something light and romantic strikes me and emily giffen is usually good for that. üìö ‚Äúall i ever wanted‚Äù opens from the  perspective of nina browning, the wife of a wealthy business man and mother to an 18 year old son, finch. while at a gala where nina and her husband are being honored for their contributions, nina learns that finch has shared a sexually inappropriate snapchat photo of a teen girl. tom volpe is the single, working class father of the teen girl featured in the photo. seeking justice for his daughter lyla, tom escalates the situation the dean of lyla and finch‚Äôs private school windsor academy. the story unfolds with point of view chapters for nina, tom, finch and lyla. üìö

the story was very engaging and incredibly timely given how much discussion there has been this year with the #metoo movement and cyber bullying. giffen ambitiously tackles several themes likes privilege, racism, infidelity, religion, rape, social media, etc. i felt that this novel was a bit outside of her wheelhouse and while i enjoyed reading it, i did wish giffen didn‚Äôt leave out the romance in favor of all of the aforementioned topics.üìö rating: ‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è #bookstagram #bookreview #2018reads #goodreads

text: i flew to minnesota for a wonderful but quick visit with friends and family this week. today on my way home i had such a horrible experience i feel it needs to be shared. i arrived at the msp airport tsa with a purse and one shoulder bag. i followed all the rules and went thru the ex ray machine only to be told i needed to be patted down. i endured it but then was told my shoulder bag needed to be opened. the man found my kindle and a 4 oz lavender lotion i just purchased from a craft fair in msp. he made me return it to the trash can and put my kindle in a tub. he demanded i get back in line and go thru the security again. i used some of the expensive lavender lotion and put everything back into tubs. after once again standing in the exray machine they made me go thru yet another pat down. when i complained i had already done this she rudely said i needed to have my hands wiped as well. i failed it because of the lotion and now they put me thru yet another extremely embarrassing pat down and they emptied my purse and my shoulder bag to wipe them down. i was extremely upset to be put thru all of this for no apparent reason. i was treated like a criminal and humiliated in front of other passengers. they put their hands inside my pants, in between my legs, down my shirt and over my breasts three times.they yelled at me when i tried to put my shoes back on and harassed me at every turn. i was made late for my flight and i felt so violated. i was dressed nicely and i did not have much carry on. i say please and thank you and treat everyone nicely. no one deserves to be treated this way at an airport for simply forgetting to pull their kindle and a lotion .5 oz over.  how is this different from me too when i was powerless to their touching me and humiliating me in front of strangers? no person regardless of race, gender or religion deserves to be treated like this. we all deserve some respect. #msptsa #airportharrassment #minnesotaniceisdead #metoo #dontwantoflyagain
